Sheltr is a browser-native terminal sharing tool for remote developers. Run one command on your machine, get two URLs — one for collaborators who can type, one for viewers who can only watch. No SSH, no screen sharing, no installing anything on the other end. Your shell stays on your machine; Sheltr's server acts purely as a relay, forwarding bytes between your terminal and anyone with the link. Sessions are recorded automatically, so when the call ends you get a replay link — a timestamped playback of everything that ran, shareable like a video but rendered as a real terminal. Built for remote pair programming, live technical interviews, and incident response war rooms where five engineers need to watch one person's server in real time.